y; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">Q37 </span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Valerie </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Vaz</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">:</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> Another statistic is </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">that</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> 25% are carcinogenic. As public health officials, do you think that is acceptable?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Dr </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Cosford</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">: If there is any risk of exposure, that would be unacceptable. The report goes through the evidence as to whether there is any risk of exposure to the public from any of the chemicals that are used and makes some stipulations about how that should be considered if there is a desire to go forward with the process.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Valerie </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Vaz</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">: Thank you.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">Q38 </span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </sp